{{Spanish name|Garro|Sánchez}}
{{Infobox officeholder | honorific-prefix = | name = Laura María Garro Sánchez | native_name = | native_name_lang = | honorific-suffix = | image = | imagesize = 100px | alt = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Costa Rica]] | party = [[Citizens' Action Party (Costa Rica)|Citizens' Action Party]] | profession = Finance, political activist | order = | office = Deputy [[Legislative Assembly of Costa Rica]] | term_start = {{Date |2014}} | term_end = {{Date |2018}} | constituency = [[Heredia Province|Heredia, Costa Rica]] }}
'''Laura María Garro Sánchez''' is a [[Costa Rica]]n educator and a current deputy from [[Heredia Province|Heredia]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Costa Rica|Legislative Assembly]].
==Education== Garro studied business at the [[National University of Costa Rica]].<ref name=ojo>{{cite web|title=Ojo al Voto: Laura María Garro Sánchez|url=http://www.ojoalvoto.com/actores/laura-maria-garro-sanchez#.U1fOmlceeVo|work=media consortium voting guide|publisher=Ojo al Voto|accessdate=23 April 2014|location=San Jose|language=es}}</ref> She earned a Master's in business administration from the Autonomous University of Central America.<ref name=ojo />
==Business career== [[File:Boulevard del Paseo de los Turistas. Puntarenas. Costa Rica..JPG|thumb|One of Garro's stated goals is to improve tourism in Puntarenas, such as the Tourists' Boulevard]] Garro worked for 25 years in public banking and finance.<ref name=ojo />
==Political career== Garro is a member of the [[Citizens' Action Party (Costa Rica)|Citizens' Action Party]] (PAC for its Spanish initials). She has been a provincial secretary, cantonal president, and party congressional participant.<ref name=ojo />
While running for mayor of Puntarenas in 2006 for PAC, Garro said that she wanted to improve tourist infrastructure in Puntarenas. She also wanted to create better opportunities for citizens.<ref name=alcalde>{{cite news|last=Villalobos|first=Carlos|title=Candidatos a alcalde: Cantones de Puntarenas|url=http://wvw.nacion.com/ln_ee/2006/noviembre/27/pais905165.html|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=La Nacion|date=27 November 2006|location=San Jose|language=es}}</ref> She lost the election.
Garro was elected deputy to the Legislative Assembly in 2014.<ref name=mapa>{{cite news|title=RESULTADOS ELECTORALES EN MAPA ELECTORAL|url=http://www.nacion.com/gnfactory/especiales/2014/diputados4/index.html|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=La Nacion|date=2014|location=San Jose|language=es}}</ref> At the time of her election to deputy, Garro was 62 years old.<ref name=su>{{cite news|title=Candidatos a Diputado|url=http://www.semanariouniversidad.ucr.cr/noticias/candidatos-diputado/12097-puntarenas.html|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=Semanario Universidad|date=11 December 2013|language=es}}</ref> She will serve alongside [[Henry Mora Jiménez]], another PAC member also from Heredia.
She became second pro-secretary of the Legislative Assembly on 1 May 2014.<ref>[http://www.nacion.com/nacional/politica/PAC-logra-presidencia-directorio-legislativo_0_1411858902.html Rupturas y últimos amarres complicaron elección de presidente legislativo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502224955/http://www.nacion.com/nacional/politica/PAC-logra-presidencia-directorio-legislativo_0_1411858902.html |date=2014-05-02 }} La Nación, 2014-05-01 {{es}}</ref>
